Alkhurma Hemorrhagic Fever (AHF) is a rare but severe viral disease that affects humans and likely animals, caused by the Alkhurma virus. The treatment market for Alkhurma Hemorrhagic Fever is segmented based on treatment type and end-user. In terms of treatment type, the market is categorized into supportive care, antiviral medications, and vaccines. Supportive care includes managing symptoms and complications to improve the patient's condition. Antiviral medications target the virus directly to reduce its replication and spread in the body. Vaccines aim to prevent the disease by priming the immune system to recognize and fight off the virus. Regarding end-users, the market serves hospitals, clinics, research institutes, and other healthcare facilities involved in the diagnosis and treatment of AHF patients.

